EXPERIMENTAL FARM, YUKON TERRITORY

Mr. Black (Yukon):

1. What has the establishment and operation by the government of an experimental farm about 100 miles from Whitehorse in Yukon Territory cost. showing items of expenditure including salaries and wages?

2. What ﬁnancial returns have there been from said farm?

3. What new agricultural information has been obtained from the operation of said farm, informa- tion not in possession of the Department of Agricul- ture prior to the establishment of said farm?

4. What is the object of its operation? Mr. McCubbin:

1. Salaries ............... $ 11,379 . 19 Wages ................ 45,583 . 62 Miscellaneous ......... 19,296 . 66 Total ............. $ 76,259.47

2. Revenue received, $796.03.

3. Previous to the establishment of the Whitehorse experimental substation, soil sur- veys had revealed the existence of several areas of land in the southern Yukon which appeared suitable for agricultural production, but no information was available on actual crop production. The operation of this sub- station has deﬁnitely proved that fair quality wheat, as well as excellent quality barley and oats, can be produced in this district, despite the more rigorous climatic conditions as com- pared with the Dawson area, in which investi- gations had been previously conducted. It has also been proved possible to produce rea- sonably good yields of the hardy vegetables and also of forage crops for hay and grazing purposes.

4.

(a) To obtain information on the produc- tion of crops and livestock, particularly in southwestern Yukon in the region served by the Alaska highway.

(b) To obtain by conducting co—operative tests in other areas, such as Dawson and Mayo, agricultural information applicable to those districts.

[Mr. McIlraithJ

COMMONS

(c) To test under northern conditions varie- ties and practices which may be of value in other parts of northern Canada.

(d) To serve as a headquarters for the dis- semination of pertinent agricultural informa- tion to interested residents in the Yukon.
